High technology poses special challenges for unlverslties, the private sector and the government. From the university's point of view, students need sophisticated equipment on which to train, and faculty members desire contact with professionals who are experienced with the complex technology. But the equipment is so expensive and becomes obsolete so quickly that it is unrealistic to maintain such facilities and personnel on campus. From the industry's point of view, a substantial investment in plant and equipment will only provide a competitive edge as long as there are highly trained personnel to develop innovative products. From the government's point of view, the technology base will be strengthened by wide dissemination of the fruits of current research, and an aggressive research effort to prepare for future technological advancement. The consortium mode], to be described, is an effective means for universities, industry and government to cooperate to meet the challenges posed by high